******
[2]
Date: Fri 7 Dec 2012
Source: Metronews.ca [edited]
http://metronews.ca/news/edmonton/469853/six-cases-of-legionnaires-disease-confirmed-in-sw-calgary-ahs/


Officials continue to investigate what caused an outbreak of legionellosis in Calgary. Alberta Health Services has confirmed 6 cases of legionellosis, also known as Legionnaires' disease, all reported within a roughly 16 km radius in southwest Calgary.

Medical Officer of Health Dr. Judy MacDonald said Friday [7 Dec 2012] that the patients were both male and female and range in age from 51 to 78. They all live or work in the same area. "The investigation that we've done to date has certainly involved inspecting the apartments and work places where these cases reside or work, looking for anything that was unusual for their water systems, heating, plumbing," said MacDonald. "That all checked out."

Despite the concentrated area, MacDonald said none of the 6 patients know each other, and officials are at a bit of a loss as to how they were exposed to the bacteria.

All 6 cases have experienced pneumonia and were admitted to the hospital but are on the mend, health officials said. "There's been some of the cases that have been severely ill, right up to the level of intensive care," said Dr. John Conly, infectious disease specialist. "I'm pleased to report all the patients are recovering at this point in time."

Legionnaires' disease can develop in humans when water containing high concentrations of the _Legionella_ bacteria are aerosolized through things like showers, fountains and humidifiers. MacDonald said it's important to remind Calgarians that the bacteria can't be transmitted person-to-person.

Since 2004, there have been 39 cases of Legionellosis in the Calgary region.

[Byline: Katie Turner]

